The aws-load-balancer-controller IS the thing that watches your Ingress resource and creates the ALB automatically.

Without the controller:

You create Ingress resource
        ↓
Nothing happens ❌
ALB never gets created
Ingress just sits there ignored

With the controller installed:

You create Ingress resource
        ↓
Controller sees it ✅
Controller calls AWS API
        ↓
ALB auto-created ✅
Target groups auto-created ✅
Routing rules auto-configured ✅

routing and target are defined in ingress controller right?

Yes! Exactly right!
Everything is defined in the Ingress resource — the controller just reads it and creates everything in AWS automatically.

Your Ingress YAML drives everything:

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: myapp-ingress
  annotations:
    kubernetes.io/ingress.class: alb
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/scheme: internet-facing
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/certificate-arn: arn:aws:acm:...
spec:
  rules:
    - host: api.myapp.com
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /api/*
            backend:
              service:
                name: api-service        # ← target group created for this
                port:
                  number: 80
          - path: /auth/*
            backend:
              service:
                name: auth-service       # ← target group created for this
                port:
                  number: 80
          - path: /frontend/*
            backend:
              service:
                name: frontend-service   # ← target group created for this
                port:
                  number: 80

What controller creates in AWS from that YAML:

Ingress YAML                    AWS Resources created
────────────────                ─────────────────────
annotations          →          ALB settings
  scheme: internet-facing   →   internet-facing ALB
  certificate-arn       →       HTTPS listener 443

rules.host           →          ALB listener rules
  api.myapp.com      →          host-based routing rule

paths                →          ALB path-based rules
  /api/*             →          rule 1: forward to TG-1
  /auth/*            →          rule 2: forward to TG-2
  /frontend/*        →          rule 3: forward to TG-3

backend.service      →          Target Groups
  api-service        →          TG-1 (api pods registered)
  auth-service       →          TG-2 (auth pods registered)
  frontend-service   →          TG-3 (frontend pods registered)

ALB automatically does health checks. Here's how it works:

ALB Health Check Flow

ALB sends HTTP GET /health
every 30 seconds to each pod
        ↓
Pod responds:
  200 OK  → healthy   ✅ → gets traffic
  500 ERR → unhealthy ❌ → removed from target group
  no resp → unhealthy ❌ → removed from target group

Where Health Check is Configured
In your Kubernetes Service or Ingress annotation:

apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  annotations:
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/healthcheck-path: /health        // which endpoint to check
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/healthcheck-interval-seconds: "30"  // check every 30 seconds
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/healthcheck-timeout-seconds: "5"    // wait 5 seconds for response
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/healthy-threshold-count: "2"        // 2 success = mark healthy
    alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/unhealthy-threshold-count: "2"      // 2 failures = mark unhealthy

# api-service    → checks /health
# auth-service   → checks /auth/health
# frontend       → checks /

annotations:
  alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/healthcheck-path: /health   // default for all

# Override per target group using:
alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/conditions.api-service: |
  healthcheck-path: /api/health

alb.ingress.kubernetes.io/conditions.auth-service: |
  healthcheck-path: /auth/health

What Happens When Pod Fails Health Check

Pod health check fails
        ↓
ALB marks pod unhealthy
        ↓
ALB stops sending traffic to that pod
        ↓
Traffic goes to healthy pods only
        ↓
Kubernetes detects pod issue
        ↓
Kubernetes restarts the pod
        ↓
Pod comes back up
        ↓
ALB health check passes again
        ↓
Pod added back to target group ✅
---
Full picture:

ALB Health Check
      ↓
/health endpoint on your pod
      ↓
Pod checks:
  ├── am I running?         ✅
  ├── DB connected?         ✅
  ├── cache connected?      ✅
  └── all good → 200 OK     ✅
      ↓
ALB marks pod as healthy
      ↓
Traffic flows to this pod

----------------------------------------------------------
So the flow is:

You write Ingress YAML
        ↓
kubectl apply -f ingress.yaml
        ↓
AWS Load Balancer Controller sees it
        ↓
Controller calls AWS API and creates:
  ✅ ALB
  ✅ Target Group per service
  ✅ Routing rules (path + host based)
  ✅ HTTPS listener with your certificate
  ✅ HTTP → HTTPS redirect
        ↓
Pods get registered in target groups automatically
        ↓
Health checks start passing
        ↓
Traffic flows!

users access this api.myapp.com in browser right?

Yes! Exactly right.
User types api.myapp.com in browser — here is the full journey:

User types: https://api.myapp.com/api/users
                    ↓
            DNS lookup
            api.myapp.com → ALB DNS
            (e.g. myapp-alb-123.us-east-2.elb.amazonaws.com)
                    ↓
            ALB (port 443 HTTPS)
                    ↓
            ALB checks routing rules
            host = api.myapp.com
            path = /api/*
                    ↓
            Forward to Target Group 1
                    ↓
            Worker Node → api Pod
                    ↓
            Response back to user

One thing you need to set up for this to work:
DNS record in Route 53 (or any DNS provider):

api.myapp.com  →  CNAME  →  myapp-alb-123.us-east-2.elb.amazonaws.com

Without this DNS record, the browser cannot find the ALB!

or else they can access via ALB dns name right?

Yes! Exactly right.
Without a custom domain, users can directly access via ALB DNS name:

http://myapp-alb-123456.us-east-2.elb.amazonaws.com

Two ways to access:

ALB DNS is great for:

✅ Testing after deployment
✅ Development environment
✅ Verifying ALB is working before DNS setup
✅ Internal tools where URL doesn't matter

Custom domain is needed for:

✅ Production apps
✅ User facing applications
✅ SSL certificate (HTTPS)
✅ Professional appearance

So ALB DNS name is perfect for testing and dev — custom domain is for production!

Two ways to access:

+---------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------------------+
|                     | Custom Domain             | ALB DNS directly                             |
+---------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------------------+
| URL                 | https://api.myapp.com     | http://myapp-alb-123.us-east-2.elb.amazonaws.com |
| SSL                 | ✔ green padlock           | ✘ no SSL                                     |
| User friendly       | ✔ easy to remember        | ✘ hard to remember                           |
| DNS setup needed    | ✔ yes                     | ✘ no                                         |
| Cost                | Route 53 ~$0.50/month     | Free                                         |
| Production ready    | ✔                         | ✘                                            |
+---------------------+---------------------------+----------------------------------------------+

Simple summary:

+------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| Ingress YAML section   | What gets created in AWS             |
+------------------------+--------------------------------------+
| annotations            | ALB configuration                    |
| rules.host             | Host-based routing rules             |
| paths                  | Path-based routing rules             |
| backend.service        | Target Groups                        |
| certificate-arn        | HTTPS listener                       |
+------------------------+--------------------------------------+

One YAML file = entire ALB setup automated!
The controller handles all the AWS API calls for you.

